 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Calinou', 'comment_id': 526847718.0, 'datetime': '2019-08-31 17:02:46+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': '@username_0 The current asset library backend uses Slim, and I think it's a bad idea for any sizeable application:

- Slim isn't as well-maintained as other popular PHP frameworks. Its community is quite small, so it's difficult to find solutions to problems.
- The performance overhead incurred by the use of a framework isn't an issue in our case, due to the relatively low amount of traffic. (Still, frameworks make it easy to apply optilizations such as caching.)
- Most professional developers use a full-ledged framework nowadays, and using one of these frameworks makes it easier to turn them into contributors.
- Your code will look different from most other backends out there, which means contributors will have to adapt to your style and paradigms.
  - This becomes even more true as you need to scale up the application, as there's no "standard" way to do so.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
