 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Calinou', 'comment_id': 526872184.0, 'datetime': '2019-08-31 23:14:52+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': '@username_1 By "static frontend", do you mean setting up a single-page application using a static site generator? That can be done, but if we're going to rewrite the backend, we can do that directly in the backend's codebase (Laravel plays well with Vue.js).', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'mrzapp', 'comment_id': 526889123.0, 'datetime': '2019-09-01 05:44:47+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': '@username_2 sort of. I meant that instead of the asset library having a frontend built in, it would only be a web service with a REST API, and the web frontend would be a page template of the main Godot website.

I'm trying to advocate a "separation of concerns" approach first and foremost. It provides a kind of flexibility that a joint effort like this benefits a lot from:

* Developing the front- and backend independently of one another would allow us to start the work on the new static Godot website right away, including the asset library page, using the existing asset library backend as a web service.
* Focusing on the new asset library backend exclusively as a web service would keep the code base lean and readable.
* Changes to the asset library backend would not affect the frontend at all, or at least minimally, which would maximise the overall uptime and reduce the deployment complexity.
* Likewise, should the need for a new frontend arise, the backend would remain untouched.
* Making the asset library frontend a part of the main Godot website provides a smoother user experience, as they would be sharing the same codebase. Currently there's a stark UI/UX difference between the two.
* The development responsibilities would be divided sensibly, meaning that we won't be making bottlenecks out of individual developers, should they go on holiday, be too busy at work or get a flu. 

Am I selling this yet? 😅', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
